{% if deal_structure == "fund_investment" %}
═══ DEAL TYPE: FUND INVESTMENT ═══
Downside modeling for a fund-of-funds / feeder investment must address:
  • NAV deterioration at the target fund level: model NAV haircut (10%, 25%, 40%)
    and its propagation through Netz's balance sheet.
  • Gate and side-pocket activation: if the offering memorandum defines gate
    thresholds, model the liquidity trap — Netz cannot exit even if it wants to.
  • Two-layer fee continuation under stress: management fees continue even if
    performance fees are not triggered — model the drag on stressed net returns.
  • Regulatory wind-down scenario: if CIMA evidence is present, model the impact
    of Netz receiving a regulatory enforcement action during a stressed period.
  • Key service provider failure: if Zedra (Netz's administrator) exits during
    stress, model the NAV reporting gap risk and its investor confidence impact.
{% else %}
═══ DEAL TYPE: DIRECT LOAN ═══
Downside modeling for a direct credit facility must address:
  • Collateral value under stress: model LTV deterioration given collateral haircut.
  • Default probability over loan tenor: calibrate against sector delinquency data.
  • Recovery mechanics: enforcement timeline, liquidation discount, legal costs.
  • Prepayment optionality: if the borrower prepays under stress, model fee recovery.
  • Covenant breach scenario: if covenants are defined, model the recovery path
    assuming a covenant cure period, standstill, and eventual enforcement.
{% endif %}

Present downside scenarios in a MANDATORY comparison table:

